<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="353" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,737,1014]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,737,762]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Differing from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1895" box="[472,624,737,762]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Platyrhacidae</taxonomicName>
by the laterally smooth, rounded paranotal margins with thickened peritremata; ozopores located caudal to midlengths on latter, opening laterad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,737,1014]" box="[199,1117,809,834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,357,809,834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Components.</emphasis>
Two subfamilies, 
<taxonomicName box="[563,745,809,834]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Aphelidesminae">Aphelidesminae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[799,931,809,834]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Amplininae">Amplininae</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation box="[938,1113,809,834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" refId="ref4769" refString="Hoffman, R. L. (1954) FUrther stUdies on American millipeds of the family EUryUridae (Polydesmida). Journal of the Washington Academy of Science, 44, 49 - 58." type="journal article">Hoffman, 1954</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="353" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,737,1014]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,449,845,870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">
Distribution (
<figureCitation box="[362,433,845,870]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1654,1676]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,988,1630]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,988,1630]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. DistribUtion of Aphelidesmidae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1439772/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Northeastern 
<collectingRegion box="[613,699,845,870]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">
<collectingCountry box="[613,699,845,870]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[758,842,845,870]" country="Trinidad and Tobago" name="Tobago" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">
<collectingCountry box="[758,842,845,870]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Tobago</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
southward to two-thirds of the latitudinal length of 
<collectingCountry box="[151,203,882,905]" name="Peru" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Peru</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[260,328,881,906]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Brazil</collectingCountry>
primarily north of the Amazon River. The northernmost confirmed localities are in southern 
<collectingRegion country="Mexico" name="San Luis Potosi" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">San Luis Potosi</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[340,453,918,941]" country="Mexico" name="Zacatecas" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Zacatecas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[468,557,917,942]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">
<collectingCountry box="[468,557,917,942]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
; while plausible, the accuracy of the northernmost record, of 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin, 1952" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1952" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" genus="Amplinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leon">
<emphasis box="[1272,1436,917,941]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Amplinus leon</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[151,360,953,978]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" refId="ref4448" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1952) Some American polydesmid millipeds in the collection of the Chicago MUseUm of NatUral History. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 45, 553 - 584. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 45.4.553" type="journal article">Chamberlin, 1952</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from Monterey, 
<collectingRegion box="[565,711,954,978]" country="Mexico" name="Nuevo Leon" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Nuevo León</collectingRegion>
, was questioned by 
<bibRefCitation box="[952,1140,953,978]" pageId="2" pageNumber="353" refId="ref4896" refString="Hoffman, R. L. (1999) Checklist of the millipeds of North and Middle America. Firginia Museum of Natural History Special Publication, 8, 1 - 584." type="journal article">Hoffman (1999)</bibRefCitation>
, and we denote it with a question mark (?) in 
<figureCitation box="[384,451,989,1014]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1654,1676]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,988,1630]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,988,1630]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. DistribUtion of Aphelidesmidae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1439772/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="353">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
